    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b80bd48c-bfb3-4005-9adc-6ae57309d402",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 34-year-old Czech male who presents to the psychiatric outpatient clinic in Prague appearing dishevelled and visibly fatigued. He is of medium build, with dark circles under his eyes suggesting chronic sleep disruption, and speaks rapidly with pressured speech, shifting between animated enthusiasm and quiet despondency during the interview. At times his speech becomes so accelerated that words seem to collide into one another, making him temporarily difficult to understand — an expressive disruption resembling transient aphasia that he himself notices and finds distressing. He is dressed in mismatched clothes, which he dismisses with a laugh, saying he dressed in the dark after sleeping all morning.\n\nProfessionally, {patientName} works as a graphic designer at a mid-sized advertising agency in Prague. His colleagues have noticed marked fluctuations in his productivity — during high-energy periods he reportedly works through the night generating creative concepts, while during low periods he calls in sick for days at a time. He finds it increasingly difficult to maintain professional relationships because of unpredictable mood swings. He enjoys cycling along the Vltava riverbank and playing online strategy games during stable periods.\n\nSocially, {patientName} lives alone in a small apartment in Žižkov. He has a close relationship with his younger brother and occasional contact with his divorced parents. He describes his romantic life as \"complicated,\" and friends have expressed concern about episodes of hypersexuality and impulsive decision-making. He occasionally drinks beer with colleagues but denies regular alcohol excess. He smokes about 5 cigarettes per day.\n\nDuring the current visit, {patientName} describes a recent full manic episode lasting approximately three weeks, characterised by a markedly elevated and then irritable mood, severely decreased need for sleep (often only 2–3 hours per night), racing thoughts, psychomotor agitation, grandiosity, and reckless spending. During the height of this episode he harboured a fixed grandiose delusion that he had been specially chosen to redesign the visual identity of the entire city of Prague, and he spent his savings commissioning printing equipment toward this end. He also reports a troubling perceptual experience during a sleep-deprived night — he briefly saw a figure that appeared to be himself standing in the corner of his room (an autoscopic hallucination), which frightened him. He has also experienced periods of profound anhedonia, hypersomnia lasting up to 14 hours per day, and fatigue that made even basic tasks impossible. He denies active suicidal ideation at present but admits to passive thoughts during the most recent depressive phase. Notably, during a prior depressive episode he suffered a minor fall from a swing in a park near his home while in a dissociated, low-energy state, resulting in a minor wrist contusion."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
